# The APIs Our App Needs

For the MVP, we need these APIs:

| API                  | Purpose                   |
| -------------------- | ------------------------- |
| POST /register       | Create a new account      |
| POST /login          | User login                |
| POST /upload-report  | Upload PDF/photo          |
| POST /confirm-values | Save corrected OCR values |
| GET /reports         | View report history       |
| GET /report/{id}     | View one report           |
| GET /compare         | Compare reports           |
| GET /profile         | View profile              |
| PUT /profile         | Update profile            |

Notice how each API has **one clear responsibility**.

---

# Types of API Requests

The two most important types you'll hear about are:

### GET

Used to **retrieve** information.

Examples:

```text
GET /reports

GET /profile
```

Think:

> "Give me information."

---

### POST

Used to **send** information.

Examples:

```text
POST /login

POST /upload-report
```

Think:

> "Here is some new information."

---

# Simple Rule to Remember

| Action        | API Type |
| ------------- | -------- |
| Read data     | GET      |
| Send new data | POST     |

Later, developers may also use:

* PUT → Update data
* DELETE → Remove data

But for now, remember GET and POST.

---

# The Complete API Flow

```text
User Uploads Report

↓

Mobile App

↓

POST /upload-report

↓

Backend

↓

Store PDF

↓

OCR

↓

Return Values

↓

User Reviews

↓

POST /confirm-values

↓

AI Analysis

↓

Database Saves Everything

↓

History Updated
```

Every action in your app follows a similar pattern.

---

# Why APIs Are Powerful

Imagine one day you build:

* Android app
* iPhone app
* Website

Do you need three different backends?

**No.**

All three can use the same APIs.

That's why APIs are so important—they allow different applications to communicate with the same system.

